# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: k-means-clustering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] In mathematics and physics, the **centroid**, also known as **geometric center** or **center of figure**, of a plane figure or solid figure is the mean position of all the points in the figure.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The same definition extends to any object in n -dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] In geometry, one often assumes uniform mass density, in which case the *barycenter* or *center of mass* coincides with the centroid.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Informally, it can be understood as the point at which a cutout of the shape (with uniformly distributed mass) could be perfectly balanced on the tip of a pin.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] In physics, if variations in gravity are considered, then a *center of gravity* can be defined as the weighted mean of all points weighted by their specific weight.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] In geography, the centroid of a radial projection of a region of the Earth's surface to sea level is the region's geographical center.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] It is used as a substitute for the older terms "center of gravity" and "center of mass" when the purely geometrical aspects of that point are to be emphasized.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The term is particular to the English language; French, for instance, uses "*centre de gravité*" on most occasions, and other languages use terms of similar meaning.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The center of gravity, as the name indicates, is a notion that arose in mechanics, most likely in connection with building activities.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] It is uncertain when the idea first appeared, as the concept likely occurred to many people individually with minor differences.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Nonetheless, the center of gravity of figures was studied extensively in Antiquity; Bossut credits Archimedes (287–212 BCE) with being the first to find the centroid of plane figures, although he never defines it.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] A treatment of centroids of solids by Archimedes has been lost.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] It is unlikely that Archimedes learned the theorem that the medians of a triangle meet in a point—the center of gravity of the triangle—directly from Euclid, as this proposition is not in the *Elements*.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The first explicit statement of this proposition is due to Heron of Alexandria (perhaps the first century CE) and occurs in his *Mechanics*.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] It may be added, in passing, that the proposition did not become common in the textbooks on plane geometry until the nineteenth century.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The geometric centroid of a convex object always lies in the object.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] A non-convex object might have a centroid that is outside the figure itself.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of a ring or a bowl, for example, lies in the object's central void.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] If the centroid is defined, it is a fixed point of all isometries in its symmetry group.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] In particular, the geometric centroid of an object lies in the intersection of all its hyperplanes of symmetry.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of many figures (regular polygon, regular polyhedron, cylinder, rectangle, rhombus, circle, sphere, ellipse, ellipsoid, superellipse, superellipsoid, etc.) can be determined by this principle alone.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] In particular, the centroid of a parallelogram is the meeting point of its two diagonals.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] This is not true of other quadrilaterals.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] For the same reason, the centroid of an object with translational symmetry is undefined (or lies outside the enclosing space), because a translation has no fixed point.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of a triangle is the intersection of the three medians of the triangle (each median connecting a vertex with the midpoint of the opposite side).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] For other properties of a triangle's centroid, see below.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of a uniformly dense planar lamina, such as in figure (a) below, may be determined experimentally by using a plumbline and a pin to find the collocated center of mass of a thin body of uniform density having the same shape.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The body is held by the pin, inserted at a point, off the presumed centroid in such a way that it can freely rotate around the pin; the plumb line is then dropped from the pin (figure b).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The position of the plumbline is traced on the surface, and the procedure is repeated with the pin inserted at any different point (or a number of points) off the centroid of the object.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The unique intersection point of these lines will be the centroid (figure c).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Provided that the body is of uniform density, all lines made this way will include the centroid, and all lines will cross at exactly the same place.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] This method can be extended (in theory) to concave shapes where the centroid may lie outside the shape, and virtually to solids (again, of uniform density), where the centroid may lie within the body.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The (virtual) positions of the plumb lines need to be recorded by means other than by drawing them along the shape.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] For convex two-dimensional shapes, the centroid can be found by balancing the shape on a smaller shape, such as the top of a narrow cylinder.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid occurs somewhere within the range of contact between the two shapes (and exactly at the point where the shape would balance on a pin).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] In principle, progressively narrower cylinders can be used to find the centroid to arbitrary precision.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] In practice air currents make this infeasible.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] However, by marking the overlap range from multiple balances, one can achieve a considerable level of accuracy.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] For example, the figure below (a) is easily divided into a square and a triangle, both with positive area; and a circular hole, with negative area (b).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of each part can be found in any list of centroids of simple shapes (c).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Then the centroid of the figure is the weighted average of the three points.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The same formula holds for any three-dimensional objects, except that each $A_{i}$ should be the volume of $X_{i},$ rather than its area.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] It also holds for any subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{d},$ for any dimension $d,$ with the areas replaced by the d -dimensional measures of the parts.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] where the integrals are taken over the whole space $\mathbb {R} ^{n},$ and g is the characteristic function of the subset X of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\!:\ g(x)=1$ if $x\in X$ and $g(x)=0$ otherwise.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Note that the denominator is simply the measure of the set $X.$ This formula cannot be applied if the set X has zero measure, or if either integral diverges.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] where A is the area of the region (given by ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}{\bigl (}f(x)-g(x){\bigr )}dx}$ ).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] An integraph (a relative of the planimeter) can be used to find the centroid of an object of irregular shape with smooth (or piecewise smooth) boundary.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The mathematical principle involved is a special case of Green's theorem.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] This is a method of determining the centroid of an L-shaped object.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Divide the shape into two other rectangles, as shown in fig 3.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Find the centroids of these two rectangles by drawing the diagonals.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] As the centroid of the shape must lie along $AB$ and also along $CD,$ it must be at the intersection of these two lines, at $O.$ The point O might lie inside or outside the L-shaped object.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of a triangle is the point of intersection of its medians (the lines joining each vertex with the midpoint of the opposite side).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid divides each of the medians in the ratio $2:1,$ which is to say it is located ${\tfrac {1}{3}}$ of the distance from each side to the opposite vertex (see figures at right).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Its Cartesian coordinates are the means of the coordinates of the three vertices.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid is also the physical center of mass if the triangle is made from a uniform sheet of material; or if all the mass is concentrated at the three vertices, and evenly divided among them.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] On the other hand, if the mass is distributed along the triangle's perimeter, with uniform linear density, then the center of mass lies at the Spieker center (the incenter of the medial triangle), which does not (in general) coincide with the geometric centroid of the full triangle.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The area of the triangle is ${\tfrac {3}{2}}$ times the length of any side times the perpendicular distance from the side to the centroid.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The isogonal conjugate of a triangle's centroid is its symmedian point.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Any of the three medians through the centroid divides the triangle's area in half.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] A triangle's centroid is the point that maximizes the product of the directed distances of a point from the triangle's sidelines.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Let $ABC$ be a triangle, let G be its centroid, and let $D,E,F$ be the midpoints of segments $BC,CA,AB,$ respectively.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of a non-triangular polygon is not the same as its *vertex centroid*, considering only its vertex set (as the centroid of a finite set of points; ).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of a cone or pyramid is located on the line segment that connects the apex to the centroid of the base.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] For a solid cone or pyramid, the centroid is ${\tfrac {1}{4}}$ the distance from the base to the apex.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] For a cone or pyramid that is just a shell (hollow) with no base, the centroid is ${\tfrac {1}{3}}$ the distance from the base plane to the apex.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] A tetrahedron is an object in three-dimensional space having four triangles as its faces.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] A line segment joining a vertex of a tetrahedron with the centroid of the opposite face is called a *median*, and a line segment joining the midpoints of two opposite edges is called a *bimedian*.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] Hence there are four medians and three bimedians.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] These seven line segments all meet at the *centroid* of the tetrahedron.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The medians are divided by the centroid in the ratio $3:1.$ The centroid of a tetrahedron is the midpoint between its Monge point and circumcenter (center of the circumscribed sphere).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] These three points define the *Euler line* of the tetrahedron that is analogous to the Euler line of a triangle.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] These results generalize to any n -dimensional simplex in the following way.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The geometric centroid coincides with the center of mass if the mass is uniformly distributed over the whole simplex, or concentrated at the vertices as $n+1$ equal masses.
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of a solid hemisphere (i.e. half of a solid ball) divides the line segment connecting the sphere's center to the hemisphere's pole in the ratio $3:5$ (i.e. it lies ${\tfrac {3}{8}}$ of the way from the center to the pole).
[src:k-means-clustering/centroid] The centroid of a hollow hemisphere (i.e. half of a hollow sphere) divides the line segment connecting the sphere's center to the hemisphere's pole in half.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis refers to a family of algorithms and tasks rather than one specific algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] It can be achieved by various algorithms that differ significantly in their understanding of what constitutes a cluster and how to efficiently find them.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Popular notions of clusters include groups with small distances between cluster members, dense areas of the data space, intervals or particular statistical distributions.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Clustering can therefore be formulated as a multi-objective optimization problem.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The appropriate clustering algorithm and parameter settings (including parameters such as the distance function to use, a density threshold or the number of expected clusters) depend on the individual data set and intended use of the results.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis as such is not an automatic task, but an iterative process of knowledge discovery or interactive multi-objective optimization that involves trial and failure.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] It is often necessary to modify data preprocessing and model parameters until the result achieves the desired properties.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Besides the term *clustering*, there are a number of terms with similar meanings, including *automatic classification*, *numerical taxonomy*, *botryology* (from Greek: βότρυς 'grape'), *typological analysis*, and *community detection*.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The subtle differences are often in the use of the results: while in data mining, the resulting groups are the matter of interest, in automatic classification the resulting discriminative power is of interest.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis originated in anthropology by Driver and Kroeber in 1932 and introduced to psychology by Joseph Zubin in 1938 and Robert Tryon in 1939 and famously used by Cattell beginning in 1943 for trait theory classification in personality psychology.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The notion of a "cluster" cannot be precisely defined, which is one of the reasons why there are so many clustering algorithms.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] There is a common denominator: a group of data objects.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] However, different researchers employ different cluster models, and for each of these cluster models again different algorithms can be given.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The notion of a cluster, as found by different algorithms, varies significantly in its properties.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Understanding these "cluster models" is key to understanding the differences between the various algorithms.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A "clustering" is essentially a set of such clusters, usually containing all objects in the data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, it may specify the relationship of the clusters to each other, for example, a hierarchy of clusters embedded in each other.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] As listed above, clustering algorithms can be categorized based on their cluster model.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The following overview will only list the most prominent examples of clustering algorithms, as there are possibly over 100 published clustering algorithms.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Not all provide models for their clusters and can thus not easily be categorized.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] An overview of algorithms explained in Wikipedia can be found in the list of statistics algorithms.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The most appropriate clustering algorithm for a particular problem often needs to be chosen experimentally, unless there is a mathematical reason to prefer one cluster model over another.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] An algorithm that is designed for one kind of model will generally fail on a data set that contains a radically different kind of model.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means cannot find non-convex clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Most traditional clustering methods assume the clusters exhibit a spherical, elliptical or convex shape.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Connectivity-based clustering, also known as hierarchical clustering, is based on the idea that objects are more related to nearby objects than to those farther away.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] These algorithms form clusters by connecting objects based on their distance.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A cluster can be understood in terms of the maximum distance required to connect its elements.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] At different distance thresholds, different cluster groupings appear.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] These groupings can be visualized using a dendrogram, a tree-like diagram that shows how clusters merge as the distance increases.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This explains the term "hierarchical clustering": instead of producing a single partition of the data set, the algorithm builds a hierarchy of clusters that merge at different distances.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In a dendrogram, the y-axis shows the distance at which clusters merge, while the x-axis arranges objects so that clusters appear as continuous branches.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Connectivity-based clustering is a family of methods that differ in how distances between clusters are computed.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In addition to choosing a distance function, the user must also select a **linkage criterion**, which determines how the distance between clusters is calculated.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Common linkage criteria include single-linkage clustering (minimum distance between points), complete linkage clustering (maximum distance), and UPGMA or WPGMA (average linkage based on mean distances).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Hierarchical clustering can be either agglomerative (starting with individual elements and merging them) or divisive (starting with the full data set and splitting it).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Identify the two closest clusters based on a chosen distance measure.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Recalculate distances between the new cluster and the remaining clusters using the selected linkage criterion.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Repeat until all data points are merged into a single cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This process produces a full hierarchy of possible clusterings rather than a single final result.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A specific clustering can be obtained by selecting a cut level in the dendrogram, which determines how many clusters are formed.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] These methods do not produce a unique partitioning of the data set, but rather a hierarchy from which the user must choose appropriate clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] They are also sensitive to outliers, which may appear as separate clusters or cause other clusters to merge.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This effect, especially in single-linkage clustering, is known as the "chaining phenomenon".
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In the general case, the complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ for agglomerative clustering and ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n-1})$ for divisive clustering, which makes them computationally expensive for large data sets.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] For some special cases, more efficient methods (with complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ ) are known, such as SLINK for single-linkage and CLINK for complete-linkage clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In centroid-based clustering, each cluster is represented by a central vector, which is not necessarily a member of the data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] When the number of clusters is fixed to *k*, *k*-means clustering gives a formal definition as an optimization problem: find the *k* cluster centers and assign the objects to the nearest cluster center, such that the squared distances from the cluster are minimized.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The optimization problem itself is known to be NP-hard, and thus the common approach is to search only for approximate solutions.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A particularly well-known approximate method is Lloyd's algorithm, often just referred to as "*k-means algorithm*" (although another algorithm introduced this name).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] It does however only find a local optimum, and is commonly run multiple times with different random initializations.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Most *k*-means-type algorithms require the number of clusters – *k* – to be specified in advance, which is considered to be one of the biggest drawbacks of these algorithms.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Furthermore, the algorithms prefer clusters of approximately similar size, as they will always assign an object to the nearest centroid; often yielding improperly cut borders of clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This happens primarily because the algorithm optimizes cluster centers, not cluster borders.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Assign each observation to the centroid to which it has the smallest squared Euclidean distance.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This results in *k* distinct groups, each containing unique observations.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Recalculate centroids (see *k*-means clustering).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Exit *iff* the new centroids are equivalent to the previous iteration's centroids.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Else, repeat the algorithm, the centroids have yet to converge.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] K-means has a number of interesting theoretical properties.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] First, it partitions the data space into a structure known as a Voronoi diagram.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Second, it is conceptually close to nearest neighbor classification, and as such is popular in machine learning.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Third, it can be seen as a variation of model-based clustering, and Lloyd's algorithm as a variation of the Expectation-maximization algorithm for this model discussed below.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The following pseudocode describes the standard iterative refinement form of *k*-means.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The algorithm alternates between an **assignment step**, which labels each point by its nearest centroid, and an **update step**, which recomputes each centroid as the mean of its assigned points.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Convergence is guaranteed in a finite number of iterations, though the result may be a local optimum.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Centroid-based clustering problems such as *k*-means and *k*-medoids are special cases of the uncapacitated, metric facility location problem, a canonical problem in the operations research and computational geometry communities.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In a basic facility location problem (of which there are numerous variants that model more elaborate settings), the task is to find the best warehouse locations to optimally service a given set of consumers.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] One may view "warehouses" as cluster centroids and "consumer locations" as the data to be clustered.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This makes it possible to apply the well-developed algorithmic solutions from the facility location literature to the presently considered centroid-based clustering problem.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The clustering framework most closely related to statistics is model-based clustering, which is based on distribution models.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This approach models the data as arising from a mixture of probability distributions.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] It has the advantages of providing principled statistical answers to questions such as how many clusters there are, what clustering method or model to use, and how to detect and deal with outliers.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] While the theoretical foundation of these methods is excellent, they suffer from overfitting unless constraints are put on the model complexity.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A more complex model will usually be able to explain the data better, which makes choosing the appropriate model complexity inherently difficult.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Standard model-based clustering methods include more parsimonious models based on the eigenvalue decomposition of the covariance matrices, that provide a balance between overfitting and fidelity to the data.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] One prominent method is known as Gaussian mixture models (using the expectation-maximization algorithm).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Here, the data set is usually modeled with a fixed (to avoid overfitting) number of Gaussian distributions that are initialized randomly and whose parameters are iteratively optimized to better fit the data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This will converge to a local optimum, so multiple runs may produce different results.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In order to obtain a hard clustering, objects are often then assigned to the Gaussian distribution they most likely belong to; for soft clusterings, this is not necessary.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Distribution-based clustering produces complex models for clusters that can capture correlation and dependence between attributes.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] However, these algorithms put an extra burden on the user: for many real data sets, there may be no concisely defined mathematical model (e.g. assuming Gaussian distributions is a rather strong assumption on the data).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In density-based clustering, clusters are defined as areas of higher density than the remainder of the data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Objects in sparse areas – that are required to separate clusters – are usually considered to be noise and border points.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The most popular density-based clustering method is DBSCAN.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In contrast to many newer methods, it features a well-defined cluster model called "density-reachability".
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Similar to linkage-based clustering, it is based on connecting points within certain distance thresholds.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] However, it only connects points that satisfy a density criterion, in the original variant defined as a minimum number of other objects within this radius.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A cluster consists of all density-connected objects (which can form a cluster of an arbitrary shape, in contrast to many other methods) plus all objects that are within these objects' range.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] OPTICS is a generalization of DBSCAN that removes the need to choose an appropriate value for the range parameter $\varepsilon$ , and produces a hierarchical result related to that of linkage clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] DeLi-Clu, Density-Link-Clustering combines ideas from single-linkage clustering and OPTICS, eliminating the $\varepsilon$ parameter entirely and offering performance improvements over OPTICS by using an R-tree index.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] HDBSCAN extends DBSCAN by converting it into a hierarchical clustering algorithm, and then using a technique to extract a flat clustering based in the stability of clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The key drawback of DBSCAN and OPTICS is that they expect some kind of density drop to detect cluster borders.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] On data sets with, for example, overlapping Gaussian distributions – a common use case in artificial data – the cluster borders produced by these algorithms will often look arbitrary, because the cluster density decreases continuously.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] On a data set consisting of mixtures of Gaussians, these algorithms are nearly always outperformed by methods such as EM clustering that are able to precisely model this kind of data.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Mean-shift is a clustering approach where each object is moved to the densest area in its vicinity, based on kernel density estimation.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Eventually, objects converge to local maxima of density.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Similar to k-means clustering, these "density attractors" can serve as representatives for the data set, but mean-shift can detect arbitrary-shaped clusters similar to DBSCAN.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Due to the expensive iterative procedure and density estimation, mean-shift is usually slower than DBSCAN or k-Means.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Besides that, the applicability of the mean-shift algorithm to multidimensional data is hindered by the unsmooth behaviour of the kernel density estimate, which results in over-fragmentation of cluster tails.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The grid-based technique is used for a multi-dimensional data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In this technique, we create a grid structure, and the comparison is performed on grids (also known as cells).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The grid-based technique is fast and has low computational complexity.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] There are two types of grid-based clustering methods: STING and CLIQUE.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Randomly select a cell ‘c’, where c should not be traversed beforehand.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Calculate the density of all the neighbors of ‘c’.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] If the density of a neighboring cell is greater than threshold density then, add the cell in the cluster and repeat steps 4.2 and 4.3 till there is no neighbor with a density greater than threshold density.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Repeat steps 2, 3, and 4 till all the cells are traversed.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] With the increasing need to process Big data, the willingness to trade semantic meaning of the generated clusters for performance becomes more relevant.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Therefore, efforts have been put into improving the performance of existing algorithms.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This led to the development of pre-clustering methods such as canopy clustering, which can process huge data sets efficiently, but the resulting "clusters" are merely a rough pre-partitioning of the data set to then analyze the partitions with existing slower methods such as k-means clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] For high-dimensional data, many methods fail due to the curse of dimensionality, which renders particular distance functions problematic in high-dimensional spaces.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Examples for such clustering algorithms are CLIQUE and SUBCLU.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Several different clustering systems based on mutual information have been proposed.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] One is Marina Meilă's *variation of information* metric; another provides hierarchical clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Using genetic algorithms, a wide range of different fit-functions can be optimized, including mutual information.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Also belief propagation, a recent development in computer science and statistical physics, has led to the creation of new types of clustering algorithms.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Evaluation (or "validation") of clustering results is as difficult as the clustering itself.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Internal evaluation measures suffer from the problem that they represent functions that themselves can be seen as a clustering objective.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, one could cluster the data set by the Silhouette coefficient; except that there is no known efficient algorithm for this.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] By using such an internal measure for evaluation, one rather compares the similarity of the optimization problems, and not necessarily how useful the clustering is.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] External evaluation has similar problems: if we have such "ground truth" labels, then we would not need to cluster; and in practical applications we usually do not have such labels.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] On the other hand, the labels only reflect one possible partitioning of the data set, which does not imply that there does not exist a different, and maybe even better, clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Neither of these approaches can therefore ultimately judge the actual quality of a clustering, but this needs human evaluation, which is highly subjective.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Nevertheless, such statistics can be quite informative in identifying bad clusterings, but one should not dismiss subjective human evaluation.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] When a clustering result is evaluated based on the data that was clustered itself, this is called internal evaluation.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] These methods usually assign the best score to the algorithm that produces clusters with high similarity within a cluster and low similarity between clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] One drawback of using internal criteria in cluster evaluation is that high scores on an internal measure do not necessarily result in effective information retrieval applications.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, this evaluation is biased towards algorithms that use the same cluster model.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means clustering naturally optimizes object distances, and a distance-based internal criterion will likely overrate the resulting clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Therefore, the internal evaluation measures are best suited to get some insight into situations where one algorithm performs better than another, but this shall not imply that one algorithm produces more valid results than another.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Validity as measured by such an index depends on the claim that this kind of structure exists in the data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] An algorithm designed for some kind of models has no chance if the data set contains a radically different set of models, or if the evaluation measures a radically different criterion.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means clustering can only find convex clusters, and many evaluation indexes assume convex clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] On a data set with non-convex clusters neither the use of *k*-means, nor of an evaluation criterion that assumes convexity, is sound.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Many internal evaluation measures are based on the intuition that items in the same cluster should be more similar than items in different clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The Dunn index aims to identify dense and well-separated clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] It is defined as the ratio between the minimal inter-cluster distance to maximal intra-cluster distance.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] where *d*(*i*,*j*) represents the distance between clusters *i* and *j*, and *d* '(*k*) measures the intra-cluster distance of cluster *k*.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The inter-cluster distance *d*(*i*,*j*) between two clusters may be any number of distance measures, such as the distance between the centroids of the clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Similarly, the intra-cluster distance *d* '(*k*) may be measured in a variety of ways, such as the maximal distance between any pair of elements in cluster *k*.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Since internal criterion seek clusters with high intra-cluster similarity and low inter-cluster similarity, algorithms that produce clusters with high Dunn index are more desirable.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The silhouette coefficient contrasts the average distance to elements in the same cluster with the average distance to elements in other clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Objects with a high silhouette value are considered well clustered, objects with a low value may be outliers.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This index works well with *k*-means clustering, and is also used to determine the optimal number of clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This matrix consider pairs of objects: the distance between the pair as a scoring function and the partition pairs defined true positive, true negatives, false negatives and true negatives by considering if pairs are in the same clusters of not.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This index borrow the same characteristics as the AUC in the supervised scenario including an expected value of 0.5 and vizualisation of results.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In external evaluation, clustering results are evaluated based on data that was not used for clustering, such as known class labels and external benchmarks.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Such benchmarks consist of a set of pre-classified items, and these sets are often created by (expert) humans.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Thus, the benchmark sets can be thought of as a gold standard for evaluation.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] These types of evaluation methods measure how close the clustering is to the predetermined benchmark classes.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] However, it has recently been discussed whether this is adequate for real data, or only on synthetic data sets with a factual ground truth, since classes can contain internal structure, the attributes present may not allow separation of clusters or the classes may contain anomalies.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, from a knowledge discovery point of view, the reproduction of known knowledge may not necessarily be the intended result.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In the special scenario of constrained clustering, where meta information (such as class labels) is used already in the clustering process, the hold-out of information for evaluation purposes is non-trivial.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A number of measures are adapted from variants used to evaluate classification tasks.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In place of counting the number of times a class was correctly assigned to a single data point (known as true positives), such *pair counting* metrics assess whether each pair of data points that is truly in the same cluster is predicted to be in the same cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Purity is a measure of the extent to which clusters contain a single class.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Its calculation can be thought of as follows: For each cluster, count the number of data points from the most common class in said cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Now take the sum over all clusters and divide by the total number of data points.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This measure doesn't penalize having many clusters, and more clusters will make it easier to produce a high purity.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A purity score of 1 is always possible by putting each data point in its own cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Also, purity doesn't work well for imbalanced data, where even poorly performing clustering algorithms will give a high purity value.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, if a size 1000 dataset consists of two classes, one containing 999 points and the other containing 1 point, then every possible partition will have a purity of at least 99.9%.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The Rand index computes how similar the clusters (returned by the clustering algorithm) are to the benchmark classifications.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] where $TP$ is the number of true positives, $TN$ is the number of true negatives, $FP$ is the number of false positives, and $FN$ is the number of false negatives.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The instances being counted here are the number of correct *pairwise* assignments.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] That is, $TP$ is the number of pairs of points that are clustered together in the predicted partition and in the ground truth partition, $FP$ is the number of pairs of points that are clustered together in the predicted partition but not in the ground truth partition etc.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] If the dataset is of size N, then $TP+TN+FP+FN={\binom {N}{2}}$ .
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] One issue with the Rand index is that false positives and false negatives are equally weighted.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This may be an undesirable characteristic for some clustering applications.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The F-measure addresses this concern, as does the chance-corrected adjusted Rand index.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The F-measure can be used to balance the contribution of false negatives by weighting recall through a parameter $\beta \geq 0$ .
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Let **precision** and **recall** (both external evaluation measures in themselves) be defined as follows: $P={\frac {TP}{TP+FP}}$ $R={\frac {TP}{TP+FN}}$ where P is the precision rate and R is the recall rate.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In other words, recall has no impact on the F-measure when $\beta =0$ , and increasing $\beta$ allocates an increasing amount of weight to recall in the final F-measure.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Also $TN$ is not taken into account and can vary from 0 upward without bound.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index is used to quantify the similarity between two datasets.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index takes on a value between 0 and 1.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] An index of 1 means that the two dataset are identical, and an index of 0 indicates that the datasets have no common elements.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index is defined by the following formula: $J(A,B)={\frac {|A\cap B|}{|A\cup B|}}={\frac {TP}{TP+FP+FN}}$ This is simply the number of unique elements common to both sets divided by the total number of unique elements in both sets.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Note that $TN$ is not taken into account.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The Dice symmetric measure doubles the weight on $TP$ while still ignoring $TN$ : $DSC={\frac {2TP}{2TP+FP+FN}}$ .
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The Fowlkes–Mallows index computes the similarity between the clusters returned by the clustering algorithm and the benchmark classifications.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The higher the value of the Fowlkes–Mallows index the more similar the clusters and the benchmark classifications are.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] It can be computed using the following formula: $FM={\sqrt {{\frac {TP}{TP+FP}}\cdot {\frac {TP}{TP+FN}}}}$ where $TP$ is the number of true positives, $FP$ is the number of false positives, and $FN$ is the number of false negatives.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The $FM$ index is the geometric mean of the precision and recall P and R , and is thus also known as the G-measure, while the F-measure is their harmonic mean.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Moreover, precision and recall are also known as Wallace's indices $B^{I}$ and $B^{II}$ .
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Chance normalized versions of recall, precision and G-measure correspond to Informedness, Markedness and Matthews Correlation and relate strongly to Kappa.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The Chi index is an external validation index that measure the clustering results by applying the chi-squared statistic.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] This index scores positively the fact that the labels are as sparse as possible across the clusters, i.e., that each cluster has as few different labels as possible.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The higher the value of the Chi Index the greater the relationship between the resulting clusters and the label used.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The mutual information is an information theoretic measure of how much information is shared between a clustering and a ground-truth classification that can detect a non-linear similarity between two clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Normalized mutual information is a family of corrected-for-chance variants of this that has a reduced bias for varying cluster numbers.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] A confusion matrix can be used to quickly visualize the results of a classification (or clustering) algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] It shows how different a cluster is from the gold standard cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] To measure cluster tendency is to measure to what degree clusters exist in the data to be clustered, and may be performed as an initial test, before attempting clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] One way to do this is to compare the data against random data.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] On average, random data should not have clusters .
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] uniformly randomly distributed data points.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] With this definition, uniform random data should tend to have values near to 0.5, and clustered data should tend to have values nearer to 1.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] , making this statistic largely useless in application (as real data never is remotely uniform).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] As clustering algorithms are increasingly deployed by corporations and governmental organizations to categorize populations and automate decisions with real world data, concerns regarding algorithmic bias have become more prevalent.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Because clustering is a form of unsupervised learning, it identifies patterns within existing data.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Consequently, these models can inadvertently reinforce historical inequalities already existent in the training datasets.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] In response, researchers have developed "Fair Clustering" frameworks, such as the Fairlet approach, which ensures that each cluster maintains a balanced representation of protected groups relative to the overall population.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Under the legal doctrine of disparate impact, a process is considered discriminatory if it results in disproportionately adverse outcomes for a protected class, even if the algorithm is facially neutral (i.e., it does not explicitly use attributes like race or gender).
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Unfairness often occurs through proxy variables.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] For instance, even if a dataset is stripped of race, a clustering algorithm might use ZIP codes or educational background as features.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] Because these variables are often highly related to economic status and ethnicity, the resulting clusters will effectively segregate individuals by these characteristics.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p01] The application of clustering in predictive policing has demonstrated how historical bias in data can create feedback loops.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p02] Cluster analysis is used for data analysis across a wide range of fields.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p02] In the natural sciences, techniques such as hierarchical clustering, *k*-means,dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis (PCA), and t-SNE are frequently used to make sense of the dense data.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p02] In computing and technology applications, clustering is the driving force behind machine learning's unsupervised learning, and is embedded in systems ranging from search engines to recommendation platforms.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p02] Common algorithms in this field include *k*-means, DBSCAN, mean shift, and spectral clustering, often applied after feature extraction or embedding, which are steps that map raw data, such as text, images, sensor logs, into a vector space amenable to distance based grouping.
[src:k-means-clustering/cluster-analysis-p02] In business and the social sciences, clustering is most often applied to tabular survey and transaction data, where the aim is to segment populations into consumer groups, create detailed market analysis insights, or illustrate voter preferences.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] In 2014, the algorithm was awarded the Test of Time Award (an award given to algorithms which have received substantial attention in theory and practice) at the leading data mining conference, ACM SIGKDD.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] As of July 2020, the follow-up paper "DBSCAN Revisited, Revisited: Why and How You Should (Still) Use DBSCAN" appears in the list of the 8 most downloaded articles of the prestigious ACM Transactions on Database Systems (TODS) journal.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Another follow-up, **HDBSCAN***, was initially published by Ricardo J.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Campello, David Moulavi, and Jörg Sander in 2013, then expanded upon with Arthur Zimek in 2015.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] It revises some of the original decisions such as the border points, and produces a hierarchical instead of a flat result.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Ling published a closely related algorithm in "The Theory and Construction of k-Clusters" in *The Computer Journal* with an estimated runtime complexity of O(n³).
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN has a worst-case complexity of O(n²).
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The database-oriented range-query formulation of DBSCAN allows for index acceleration.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The algorithms slightly differ in their handling of border points.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Consider a set of points in some space to be clustered.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Let ε be a parameter specifying the radius of a neighborhood with respect to some point.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Now if p is a core point, then it forms a *cluster* together with all points (core or non-core) that are reachable from it.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Each cluster contains at least one core point; non-core points can be part of a cluster, but they form its "edge", since they cannot be used to reach more points.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Reachability is not a symmetric relation: by definition, only core points can reach non-core points.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The opposite is not true, so a non-core point may be reachable, but nothing can be reached from it.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Therefore, a further notion of *connectedness* is needed to formally define the extent of the clusters found by DBSCAN.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Two points p and q are density-connected if there is a point o such that both p and q are reachable from o.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] If a point is density-reachable from some point of the cluster, it is part of the cluster as well.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN requires two parameters: ε (eps) and the minimum number of points required to form a dense region (minPts).
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] It starts with an arbitrary starting point that has not been visited.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] This point's ε-neighborhood is retrieved, and if it contains sufficiently many points, a cluster is started.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Otherwise, the point is labeled as noise.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Note that this point might later be found in a sufficiently sized ε-environment of a different point and hence be made part of a cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] If a point is found to be a dense part of a cluster, its ε-neighborhood is also part of that cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Hence, all points that are found within the ε-neighborhood are added, as is their own ε-neighborhood when they are also dense.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] This process continues until the density-connected cluster is completely found.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Then, a new unvisited point is retrieved and processed, leading to the discovery of a further cluster or noise.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN can be used with any distance function (as well as similarity functions or other predicates).
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The distance function (dist) can therefore be seen as an additional parameter.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Find the connected components of *core* points on the neighbor graph, ignoring all non-core points.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Assign each non-core point to a nearby cluster if the cluster is an ε (eps) neighbor, otherwise assign it to noise.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] A naive implementation of this requires storing the neighborhoods in step 1, thus requiring substantial memory.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The original DBSCAN algorithm does not require this by performing these steps for one point at a time.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] where $d_{db}(p,q)$ gives the smallest $\varepsilon$ such that two points p and q are density-connected.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN visits each point of the database, possibly multiple times (e.g., as candidates to different clusters).
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] For practical considerations, however, the time complexity is mostly governed by the number of regionQuery invocations.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Without the use of an accelerating index structure, or on degenerated data (e.g. all points within a distance less than ε), the worst case run time complexity remains O(*n*²).
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The $\textstyle {\binom {n}{2}}$ - *n* = (*n*²-*n*)/2-sized upper triangle of the distance matrix can be materialized to avoid distance recomputations, but this needs O(*n*²) memory, whereas a non-matrix based implementation of DBSCAN only needs O(*n*) memory.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN can find arbitrarily-shaped clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] It can even find a cluster completely surrounded by (but not connected to) a different cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Due to the MinPts parameter, the so-called single-link effect (different clusters being connected by a thin line of points) is reduced.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN has a notion of noise, and is robust to outliers.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN requires just two parameters and is mostly insensitive to the ordering of the points in the database.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN is designed for use with databases that can accelerate region queries, e.g. using an R* tree.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The parameters minPts and ε can be set by a domain expert, if the data is well understood.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The quality of DBSCAN depends on the distance measure used in the function regionQuery(P,ε).
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The most common distance metric used is Euclidean distance.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Especially for high-dimensional data, this metric can be rendered almost useless due to the so-called "Curse of dimensionality", making it difficult to find an appropriate value for ε.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] This effect, however, is also present in any other algorithm based on Euclidean distance.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN cannot cluster data sets well with large differences in densities, since the minPts-ε combination cannot then be chosen appropriately for all clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] If the data and scale are not well understood, choosing a meaningful distance threshold ε can be difficult.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] See the section below on extensions for algorithmic modifications to handle these issues.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Every data mining task has the problem of parameters.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Every parameter influences the algorithm in specific ways.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] For DBSCAN, the parameters ε and *minPts* are needed.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The parameters must be specified by the user.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Ideally, the value of ε is given by the problem to solve (e.g. a physical distance), and *minPts* is then the desired minimum cluster size.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] OPTICS can be seen as a generalization of DBSCAN that replaces the ε parameter with a maximum value that mostly affects performance.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] *MinPts* then essentially becomes the minimum cluster size to find.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] While the algorithm is much easier to parameterize than DBSCAN, the results are a bit more difficult to use, as it will usually produce a hierarchical clustering instead of the simple data partitioning that DBSCAN produces.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Recently, one of the original authors of DBSCAN has revisited DBSCAN and OPTICS, and published a refined version of hierarchical DBSCAN (HDBSCAN*), which no longer has the notion of border points.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Instead, only the core points form the cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] A spectral implementation of DBSCAN is related to spectral clustering in the trivial case of determining connected graph components — the optimal clusters with no edges cut.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] However, it can be computationally intensive, up to $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Additionally, one has to choose the number of eigenvectors to compute.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] For performance reasons, the original DBSCAN algorithm remains preferable to its spectral implementation.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Generalized DBSCAN (GDBSCAN) is a generalization by the same authors to arbitrary "neighborhood" and "dense" predicates.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The ε and *minPts* parameters are removed from the original algorithm and moved to the predicates.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] For example, on polygon data, the "neighborhood" could be any intersecting polygon, whereas the density predicate uses the polygon areas instead of just the object count.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Various extensions to the DBSCAN algorithm have been proposed, including methods for parallelization, parameter estimation, and support for uncertain data.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The basic idea has been extended to hierarchical clustering by the OPTICS algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] DBSCAN is also used as part of subspace clustering algorithms like PreDeCon and SUBCLU.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] HDBSCAN* is a hierarchical version of DBSCAN which is also faster than OPTICS, from which a flat partition consisting of the most prominent clusters can be extracted from the hierarchy.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] Different implementations of the same algorithm were found to exhibit enormous performance differences, with the fastest on a test data set finishing in 1.4 seconds, the slowest taking 13803 seconds.
[src:k-means-clustering/dbscan] The differences can be attributed to implementation quality, language and compiler differences, and the use of indexes for acceleration.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:k-means-clustering/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The problem is computationally difficult (NP-hard); however, efficient heuristic algorithms converge quickly to a local optimum.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] These are usually similar to the expectation–maximization algorithm for mixtures of Gaussian distributions via an iterative refinement approach employed by both *k-means* and *Gaussian mixture modeling*.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] They both use cluster centers to model the data; however, *k*-means clustering tends to find clusters of comparable spatial extent, while the Gaussian mixture model allows clusters to have different shapes.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The unsupervised *k*-means algorithm has a loose relationship to the *k*-nearest neighbor classifier, a popular supervised machine learning technique for classification that is often confused with *k*-means due to the name.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Applying the 1-nearest neighbor classifier to the cluster centers obtained by *k*-means classifies new data into the existing clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This is known as nearest centroid classifier or Rocchio algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Since the total variance is constant, this is equivalent to maximizing the sum of squared deviations between points in *different* clusters (between-cluster sum of squares, BCSS).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This deterministic relationship is also related to the law of total variance in probability theory.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The term "*k*-means" was first used by James MacQueen in 1967, though the idea goes back to Hugo Steinhaus in 1956.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The standard algorithm was first proposed by Stuart Lloyd of Bell Labs in 1957 as a technique for pulse-code modulation, although it was not published as a journal article until 1982.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Forgy published essentially the same method, which is why it is sometimes referred to as the Lloyd–Forgy algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Early applications of the k-means algorithm were primarily found in signal processing and data compression, particularly in the context of vector quantization.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Lloyd's work at Bell Labs focused on representing analog signals using a limited set of discrete values, where clustering was used to reduce the amount of data required while preserving signal quality.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] As computing power increased, k-means clustering became widely used in pattern recognition and statistical classification due to its simplicity and computational efficiency.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] It was later adopted in early machine learning and data analysis tasks involving large datasets.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Despite its widespread use, limitations such as sensitivity to initial centroid placement and difficulty handling non-spherical clusters were recognized early on, motivating the development of improved clustering methods and initialization techniques.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The most common algorithm uses an iterative refinement technique.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Due to its ubiquity, it is often called "the *k*-means algorithm"; it is also referred to as Lloyd's algorithm, particularly in the computer science community.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] It is sometimes also referred to as "naïve *k*-means", because there exist much faster alternatives.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] **Update step**: Recalculate means (centroids) for observations assigned to each cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The objective function in *k*-means is the WCSS (within cluster sum of squares).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] After each iteration, the WCSS monotonically decreases, giving a nonnegative monotonically decreasing sequence.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This guarantees that the *k*-means always converges, but not necessarily to the global optimum.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The algorithm has converged when the assignments no longer change or equivalently, when the WCSS has become stable.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The algorithm is not guaranteed to find the optimal cluster assignment.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The algorithm is often presented as assigning objects to the nearest cluster by distance.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Using a different distance function other than (squared) Euclidean distance may prevent the algorithm from converging.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Various modifications of *k*-means such as spherical *k*-means and *k*-medoids have been proposed to allow using other distance measures.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The below pseudocode outlines the implementation of the standard *k*-means clustering algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Initialization of centroids, distance metric between points and centroids, and the calculation of new centroids are design choices and will vary with different implementations.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In this example pseudocode, `distance()` returns the distance between the specified points.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Commonly used initialization methods are Forgy and Random Partition.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The Forgy method randomly chooses *k* observations from the dataset and uses these as the initial means.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The Random Partition method first randomly assigns a cluster to each observation and then proceeds to the update step, thus computing the initial mean to be the centroid of the cluster's randomly assigned points.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The Forgy method tends to spread the initial means out, while Random Partition places all of them close to the center of the data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] According to Hamerly et al., the Random Partition method is generally preferable for algorithms such as the *k*-harmonic means and fuzzy *k*-means.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] For expectation maximization and standard *k*-means algorithms, the Forgy method of initialization is preferable.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] A comprehensive study by Celebi et al., however, found that popular initialization methods such as Forgy, Random Partition, and Maximin often perform poorly, whereas Bradley and Fayyad's approach performs "consistently" in "the best group" and *k*-means++ performs "generally well".
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The algorithm does not guarantee convergence to the global optimum.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The result may depend on the initial clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] As the algorithm is usually fast, it is common to run it multiple times with different starting conditions.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] However, worst-case performance can be slow: in particular certain point sets, even in two dimensions, converge in exponential time, that is 2Ω(*n*).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] These point sets do not seem to arise in practice: this is corroborated by the fact that the smoothed running time of *k*-means is polynomial.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The "assignment" step is referred to as the "expectation step", while the "update step" is a maximization step, making this algorithm a variant of the *generalized* expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Thus, a variety of heuristic algorithms such as Lloyd's algorithm given above are generally used.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] On data that does have a clustering structure, the number of iterations until convergence is often small, and results only improve slightly after the first dozen iterations.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Lloyd's algorithm is therefore often considered to be of "linear" complexity in practice, although it is in the worst case superpolynomial when performed until convergence.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Lloyd's algorithm is the standard approach for this problem.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] However, it spends a lot of processing time computing the distances between each of the *k* cluster centers and the *n* data points.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Since points usually stay in the same clusters after a few iterations, much of this work is unnecessary, making the naïve implementation very inefficient.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Some implementations use caching and the triangle inequality in order to create bounds and accelerate Lloyd's algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Finding the optimal number of clusters (*k*) for *k*-means clustering is a crucial step to ensure that the clustering results are meaningful and useful.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Several techniques are available to determine a suitable number of clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Hartigan and Wong's method provides a variation of *k*-means algorithm which progresses towards a local minimum of the minimum sum-of-squares problem with different solution updates.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The method is a local search that iteratively attempts to relocate a sample into a different cluster as long as this process improves the objective function.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] When no sample can be relocated into a different cluster with an improvement of the objective, the method stops (in a local minimum).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In a similar way as the classical *k*-means, the approach remains a heuristic since it does not necessarily guarantee that the final solution is globally optimum.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Let $\varphi (S_{j})$ be the individual cost of $S_{j}$ defined by ${\textstyle \sum _{x\in S_{j}}(x-\mu _{j})^{2}}$ , with $\mu _{j}$ the center of the cluster.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Different move acceptance strategies can be used.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In a *first-improvement* strategy, any improving relocation can be applied, whereas in a *best-improvement* strategy, all possible relocations are iteratively tested and only the best is applied at each iteration.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The former approach favors speed, whether the latter approach generally favors solution quality at the expense of additional computational time.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Initialization and restart techniques discussed in the previous sections are one alternative to find better solutions.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] More recently, global optimization algorithms based on branch-and-bound and semidefinite programming have produced ‘’provenly optimal’’ solutions for datasets with up to 4,177 entities and 20,531 features.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] As expected, due to the NP-hardness of the subjacent optimization problem, the computational time of optimal algorithms for *k*-means quickly increases beyond this size.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Optimal solutions for small- and medium-scale still remain valuable as a benchmark tool, to evaluate the quality of other heuristics.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] It is indeed known that finding better local minima of the minimum sum-of-squares clustering problem can make the difference between failure and success to recover cluster structures in feature spaces of high dimension.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] A key limitation of *k*-means is its cluster model.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The concept is based on spherical clusters that are separable so that the mean converges towards the cluster center.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The clusters are expected to be of similar size, so that the assignment to the nearest cluster center is the correct assignment.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] When for example applying *k*-means with a value of $k=3$ onto the well-known Iris flower data set, the result often fails to separate the three Iris species contained in the data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] With $k=2$ , the two visible clusters (one containing two species) will be discovered, whereas with $k=3$ one of the two clusters will be split into two even parts.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In fact, $k=2$ is more appropriate for this data set, despite the data set's containing 3 *classes*.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] As with any other clustering algorithm, the *k*-means result makes assumptions that the data satisfy certain criteria.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] It works well on some data sets, and fails on others.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The result of *k*-means can be seen as the Voronoi cells of the cluster means.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Since data is split halfway between cluster means, this can lead to suboptimal splits as can be seen in the "mouse" example.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The Gaussian models used by the expectation–maximization algorithm (arguably a generalization of *k*-means) are more flexible by having both variances and covariances.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The EM result is thus able to accommodate clusters of variable size much better than *k*-means as well as correlated clusters (not in this example).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In counterpart, EM requires the optimization of a larger number of free parameters and poses some methodological issues due to vanishing clusters or badly-conditioned covariance matrices.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] *k*-means is closely related to nonparametric Bayesian modeling.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In biological applications, the limitations of standard *k*-means clustering are often addressed by adapting the distance measures used and objective functions to better reflect the structure of experimental data.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Rather than relying on Euclidean distance and variance-based measures of cluster scatter, alternative similarity metrics such as the Jaccard index are sometimes used when analyzing genomic datasets with k-means.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In these contexts, clustering may be performed directly on distance matrices, and medoids (representative data points that have the smallest average distance to every other point within a cluster) may be selected as cluster centers instead of arithmetic means.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This allows clustering methods to capture patterns of shared genomic features or co-occurrence that are not well represented in a traditional Euclidean analysis.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Clustering is widely used in biological data analysis to identify patterns in high-dimensional datasets such as gene expression profiles and genomic interaction matrices.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Techniques such as *k*-means clustering partition observations into groups based on similarity, allowing researchers to detect structure in complex datasets.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In gene expression studies, clustering is commonly used to group genes with similar expression profiles, often revealing co-regulated genes and underlying biological interactions.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In addition to gene expression analysis, clustering approaches are applied to chromatin interaction data to identify regions of coordinated activity.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Similarity measures such as the Jaccard index can be used to quantify shared features between observations, and clustering of the resulting distance matrices can reveal structural organization within the genome.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] These patterns are commonly visualized using heatmaps, where clustered regions correspond to domains of interaction or co-segregation, providing insight into the regulatory organization of the genome.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In such analyses, clustering of similarity or co-detection matrices can reveal groups of genomic windows that exhibit coordinated behavior across experimental conditions.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Clustering methods provide a practical method for uncovering biologically meaningful structure from complex datasets.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] By grouping observations with similar patterns of genomic detection, expression, or interaction, these techniques can reveal functional relationships, spatial organization within the nucleus, and regulatory behavior.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In many applications, the resulting clusters correspond to distinct biological states or structural domains, further illustrating the broad applicability of k-means clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Vector quantization, a technique commonly used in signal processing and computer graphics, involves reducing the color palette of an image to a fixed number of colors, known as *k*.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] One popular method for achieving vector quantization is through *k*-means clustering.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In this process, *k*-means is applied to the color space of an image to partition it into k clusters, with each cluster representing a distinct color in the image.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This technique is particularly useful in image segmentation tasks, where it helps identify and group similar colors together.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Example: In the field of computer graphics, *k*-means clustering is often employed for color quantization in image compression.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] By reducing the number of colors used to represent an image, file sizes can be significantly reduced without significant loss of visual quality.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] For instance, consider an image with millions of colors.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] By applying *k*-means clustering with *k* set to a smaller number, the image can be represented using a more limited color palette, resulting in a compressed version that consumes less storage space and bandwidth.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Other uses of vector quantization include non-random sampling, as *k*-means can easily be used to choose *k* different but prototypical objects from a large data set for further analysis.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Cluster analysis, a fundamental task in data mining and machine learning, involves grouping a set of data points into clusters based on their similarity.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] *k*-means clustering is a popular algorithm used for partitioning data into k clusters, where each cluster is represented by its centroid.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] However, the pure *k*-means algorithm is not very flexible, and as such is of limited use (except for when vector quantization as above is actually the desired use case).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In particular, the parameter *k* is known to be hard to choose (as discussed above) when not given by external constraints.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Another limitation is that it cannot be used with arbitrary distance functions or on non-numerical data.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] For these use cases, many other algorithms are superior.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Example: In marketing, *k*-means clustering is frequently employed for market segmentation, where customers with similar characteristics or behaviors are grouped together.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] For instance, a retail company may use *k*-means clustering to segment its customer base into distinct groups based on factors such as purchasing behavior, demographics, and geographic location.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] These customer segments can then be targeted with tailored marketing strategies and product offerings to maximize sales and customer satisfaction.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This use of *k*-means has been successfully combined with simple, linear classifiers for semi-supervised learning in NLP (specifically for named-entity recognition) and in computer vision.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] On an object recognition task, it was found to exhibit comparable performance with more sophisticated feature learning approaches such as autoencoders and restricted Boltzmann machines.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] However, it generally requires more data, for equivalent performance, because each data point only contributes to one "feature".
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Example: In natural language processing (NLP), *k*-means clustering has been integrated with simple linear classifiers for semi-supervised learning tasks such as named-entity recognition (NER).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] By first clustering unlabeled text data using *k*-means, meaningful features can be extracted to improve the performance of NER models.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] For instance, *k*-means clustering can be applied to identify clusters of words or phrases that frequently co-occur in the input text, which can then be used as features for training the NER model.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This approach has been shown to achieve comparable performance with more complex feature learning techniques such as autoencoders and restricted Boltzmann machines, albeit with a greater requirement for labeled data.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Standard Lloyd’s algorithm is inherently sequential.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] It has an effective time complexity of O(nkdi), which becomes a bottleneck as the number of data points (n) or dimensions (d) increases.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This can be inefficient when used with massive, multidimensional data sets like social networks.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Various parallelization strategies have been developed to distribute the workload across multi-core processors, GPUs, and distributed clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] We see that in both parallel versions; efficiency is greatly increased for large datasets.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This speedup is significant in the OpenACC implementation, due to the massively parallel nature of GPU architectures.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Modern astronomical surveys like APOGEE and the Gaia catalog collect spectroscopic and photometric data for millions of stars, making manual classification impractical at scale.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] *K*-means clustering has been applied to this data to automatically identify distinct stellar populations based on properties like luminosity, temperature, color, and chemical abundance.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] One major application is identifying stellar populations through chemical tagging.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Stars that form together in the same cluster share similar chemical compositions, so clustering algorithms applied to abundance data can recover these groupings even after the stars have spread throughout the galaxy.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Studies using *k*-means on APOGEE infrared spectra measured abundances of up to 13 elements and successfully distinguished known star clusters from surrounding field stars.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This has also revealed populations with unusual abundance patterns that would be difficult to catch through manual inspection.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Proper initialization is very important when it comes to finding global optimum in a clustering algorithm.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Random initialization is often used for k means clustering, but this can result in poor cluster quality.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This is why the k-means++ initialization algorithm was developed.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The algorithm attempts to find initial centers that are as close to possible to the global optimum, reducing computing time and producing more accurate clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The k-means++ algorithm works by spreading out the initial cluster centers.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] It selects the first center uniformly at random from the dataset.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Each subsequent center is chosen stochastically, with the probability of a point being selected proportional to its contribution to the overall error.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This method achieves an O(log k) approximation of the optimum solution.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The primary drawback of standard k-means++ is its inherent sequential nature.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] To find k initial centers, the algorithm must make k separate passes over the data, as the selection of each new center depends on the previous choices.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This becomes prohibitively slow when clustering massive datasets into a large number of clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] To overcome these limitations, researchers developed k-means||, a parallel version of k-means++.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Instead of sampling a single point per pass, k-means|| uses an oversampling factor ℓ = Ω (k) to sample multiple points in each round.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The algorithm drastically reduces the number of passes required, obtaining a nearly optimal set of centers with a time complexity of O(log n).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] In practice, as few as five rounds are needed to reach a high-quality solution.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] After several rounds, the algorithm typically has O(log n) intermediate centers.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] These are then assigned weights based on how many points are close to them and re-clustered, often using standard k-means++, to reduce the final set to exact k centers.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The slow "standard algorithm" for *k*-means clustering, and its associated expectation–maximization algorithm, is a special case of a Gaussian mixture model, specifically, the limiting case when fixing all covariances to be diagonal, equal and have infinitesimal small variance.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Instead of small variances, a hard cluster assignment can also be used to show another equivalence of *k*-means clustering to a special case of "hard" Gaussian mixture modelling.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Another generalization of the *k*-means algorithm is the *k*-SVD algorithm, which estimates data points as a sparse linear combination of "codebook vectors".
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] *k*-means corresponds to the special case of using a single codebook vector, with a weight of 1.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The relaxed solution of *k*-means clustering, specified by the cluster indicators, is given by principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The intuition is that *k*-means describe spherically shaped (ball-like) clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] If the data has 2 clusters, the line connecting the two centroids is the best 1-dimensional projection direction, which is also the first PCA direction.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Cutting the line at the center of mass separates the clusters (this is the continuous relaxation of the discrete cluster indicator).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] If the data have three clusters, the 2-dimensional plane spanned by three cluster centroids is the best 2-D projection.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This plane is also defined by the first two PCA dimensions.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Well-separated clusters are effectively modelled by ball-shaped clusters and thus discovered by *k*-means.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Non-ball-shaped clusters are hard to separate when they are close.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] For example, two half-moon shaped clusters intertwined in space do not separate well when projected onto PCA subspace.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] *k*-means should not be expected to do well on this data.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] It is straightforward to produce counterexamples to the statement that the cluster centroid subspace is spanned by the principal directions.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Basic mean shift clustering algorithms maintain a set of data points the same size as the input data set.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Initially, this set is copied from the input set.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] All points are then iteratively moved towards the mean of the points surrounding them.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] A mean shift algorithm that is similar then to *k*-means, called *likelihood mean shift*, replaces the set of points undergoing replacement by the mean of all points in the input set that are within a given distance of the changing set.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] An advantage of mean shift clustering over *k*-means is the detection of an arbitrary number of clusters in the data set, as there is not a parameter determining the number of clusters.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Mean shift can be much slower than *k*-means, and still requires selection of a bandwidth parameter.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Under sparsity assumptions and when input data is pre-processed with the whitening transformation, *k*-means produces the solution to the linear independent component analysis (ICA) task.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] This aids in explaining the successful application of *k*-means to feature learning.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The set of squared error minimizing cluster functions also includes the *k*-medoids algorithm, an approach which forces the center point of each cluster to be one of the actual points, i.e., it uses medoids in place of centroids.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] Different implementations of the algorithm exhibit performance differences, with the fastest on a test data set finishing in 10 seconds, the slowest taking 25,988 seconds (~7 hours).
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The differences can be attributed to implementation quality, language and compiler differences, different termination criteria and precision levels, and the use of indexes for acceleration.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The following implementations are available under Free/Open Source Software licenses, with publicly available source code.
[src:k-means-clustering/k-means-clustering] The following implementations are available under proprietary license terms, and may not have publicly available source code.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Conceptually, unsupervised learning divides into the aspects of data, training, algorithm, and downstream applications.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Typically, the dataset is harvested cheaply "in the wild", such as massive text corpus obtained by web crawling, with only minor filtering (such as Common Crawl).
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] This compares favorably to supervised learning, where the dataset (such as the ImageNet1000) is typically constructed manually, which is much more expensive.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] There are algorithms designed specifically for unsupervised learning, such as clustering algorithms like k-means, dimensionality reduction techniques like principal component analysis (PCA), Boltzmann machine learning, and autoencoders.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] After the rise of deep learning, most large-scale unsupervised learning has been done by training general-purpose neural network architectures by gradient descent, adapted to performing unsupervised learning by designing an appropriate training procedure.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Sometimes a trained model can be used as-is, but more often they are modified for downstream applications.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] For example, the generative pretraining method trains a model to generate a textual dataset, before finetuning it for other applications, such as text classification.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] As another example, autoencoders are trained to produce good features, which can then be used as a module for other models, such as in a latent diffusion model.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Tasks are often categorized as discriminative (recognition) or generative (imagination).
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Often but not always, discriminative tasks use supervised methods and generative tasks use unsupervised (see Venn diagram); however, the separation is very hazy.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] For example, object recognition favors supervised learning but unsupervised learning can also cluster objects into groups.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Furthermore, as progress marches onward, some tasks employ both methods, and some tasks swing from one to another.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] For example, image recognition started off as heavily supervised, but became hybrid by employing unsupervised pre-training, and then moved towards supervision again with the advent of dropout, ReLU, and adaptive learning rates.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] A typical generative task is as follows.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] At each step, a datapoint is sampled from the dataset, and part of the data is removed, and the model must infer the removed part.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] This is particularly clear for the denoising autoencoders and BERT.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] During the learning phase, an unsupervised network tries to mimic the data it is given and uses the error in its mimicked output to correct itself (i.e. correct its weights and biases).
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Sometimes the error is expressed as a low probability that the erroneous output occurs, or it might be expressed as an unstable high energy state in the network.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] An energy function is a macroscopic measure of a network's activation state.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] In Boltzmann machines, it plays the role of the Cost function.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] This analogy with physics is inspired by Ludwig Boltzmann's analysis of a gas' macroscopic energy from the microscopic probabilities of particle motion $p\propto e^{-E/kT}$ , where k is the Boltzmann constant and T is temperature.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] In the RBM network the relation is $p=e^{-E}/Z$ , where p and E vary over every possible activation pattern and $\textstyle {Z=\sum _{\scriptscriptstyle {\text{All Patterns}}}e^{-E({\text{pattern}})}}$ .
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] To be more precise, $p(a)=e^{-E(a)}/Z$ , where a is an activation pattern of all neurons (visible and hidden).
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Hence, some early neural networks bear the name Boltzmann Machine.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Paul Smolensky calls $-E\,$ the *Harmony*.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] A network seeks low energy which is high Harmony.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] This table shows connection diagrams of various unsupervised networks, the details of which will be given in the section Comparison of Networks.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Circles are neurons and edges between them are connection weights.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] As network design changes, features are added on to enable new capabilities or removed to make learning faster.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] For instance, neurons change between deterministic (Hopfield) and stochastic (Boltzmann) to allow robust output, weights are removed within a layer (RBM) to hasten learning, or connections are allowed to become asymmetric (Helmholtz).
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Of the networks bearing people's names, only Hopfield worked directly with neural networks.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Boltzmann and Helmholtz came before artificial neural networks, but their work in physics and physiology inspired the analytical methods that were used.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Here, we highlight some characteristics of select networks.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] The details of each are given in the comparison table below.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Ferromagnetism inspired Hopfield networks.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] A neuron corresponds to an iron domain with binary magnetic moments Up and Down, and neural connections correspond to the domain's influence on each other.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Symmetric connections enable a global energy formulation.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] During inference the network updates each state using the standard activation step function.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Symmetric weights and the right energy functions guarantees convergence to a stable activation pattern.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Asymmetric weights are difficult to analyze.
[src:k-means-clustering/unsupervised-learning] Hopfield nets are used as Content Addressable Memories (CAM).
